- rework import system (@import('')) when it comes to standard library/packages vs user code vs external dependencies (need clear way to distinguish based off import statement)
- compile time decorators using '@' ???


Array Methods:
    fn push(value T) void
    fn pop() T
    fn size() usize
    fn isEmpty() bool
    fn clear() void
    fn reserve(capacity usize) void
    fn contains(value T) bool
    fn indexOf(value T) Option<usize>
    fn removeAt(index usize) T
    fn swapRemove(index usize) T
    fn insert(index usize, value T) void
    fn last() Option<T>
    fn first() Option<T>
    fn get(index usize) Option<T>
    fn set(index usize, value T) void

Set Methods:
    fn add(value T) bool         // true if newly inserted
    fn remove(value T) bool
    fn has(value T) bool
    fn size() usize
    fn isEmpty() bool
    fn clear() void

Dict Methods:
    fn set(key K, value V) void
    fn get(key K) Option<V>
    fn getOr(key K, fallback V) V
    fn has(key K) bool
    fn remove(key K) bool
    fn size() usize
    fn isEmpty() bool
    fn clear() void
    fn keys() KeyView<K>
    fn values() ValueView<V>
    fn entries() EntryView<K, V>

Possible: 
    const player Option<Player> = this.game.players.get(id)
    if (player.isSome()) {
        const p Player = player.unwrap()
    }


Loops:
for (x : container) should iterate the most natural element type of that container
    Array<T> yields T
    Set<T> yields T
    Dict<K, V> should not yield just K by default unless you are very sure

for (entry : dict) yields DictEntry<K, V>
for (key : dict.keys()) yields K
for (value : dict.values()) yields V

or possibly:
for (const (id, player) : this.players) {
    print(player.name)
}